To center a div horizontally in CSS, you can use several methods depending on the structure of your HTML and the layout you're aiming for. Here are a few common techniques:

### 1. Using `margin` Property

If you know the width of the div you want to center, you can set its `margin` property to `auto`. This works because when `margin-left` and `margin-right` are set to `auto`, they equally divide the available space on either side of the div, effectively centering it.

```css
.centered-div {
  width: 50%; /* or any specific width */
  margin: 0 auto;
}
```

### 2. Using Flexbox

Flexbox is a powerful layout system that makes it easy to center elements. If you wrap your div in a flex container and set its `justify-content` to `center`, any direct child elements will be centered horizontally.

```css
.flex-container {
  display: flex;
  justify-content: center;
}

/* Your div to be centered */
.centered-div {
  /* No need for specific width */
}
```

### 3. Using Grid Layout

CSS Grid is another layout system that provides an easy way to center elements. By setting `display` to `grid` and `justify-items` to `center`, you can center any direct child elements.

```css
.grid-container {
  display: grid;
  justify-items: center;
}

/* Your div to be centered */
.centered-div {
  /* No need for specific width */
}
```

### 4. Using Positioning

